Is College Tuition Infected? Diagnosing Baumol's Cost Disease¶

By Casey Briscoe

Background¶

Baumol's Cost Disease¶

Before explaning Baumol's Cost Disease, we must first define productivity. Productivity is a measure of the amount of economic output an average worker can produce, usually calculated as GDP divided by hours worked. As productivity rises, we can produce more goods with less labor. Some sectors, such as manufacturing, have very high and increasing productivity because of automation. Other sectors, such as healthcare and restaurants, have lower productivity that increases slowly due to lack of automation. This is for reasons such as the tasks being difficult to automate, such as cooking or healthcare, or there being a human element involved that cannot be automated, such as childcare.

Baumol's Cost Disease is a theory of wages and productivity, proposed by economist William J. Baumol in 1966. The theory states the following: As productivity in highly productive sectors rises, wages will rise with it. However, this will also affect wages in low productivity sectors as well. As workers in low-productivity sectors see the higher wages the more productive sectors demand, the low-productivity workers will move into high-productivity sectors to get paid more. Low-productivity sectors must pay more to keep their employees, and since they cannot increase productivity to lower costs, they must raise prices for the consumer. This theory plays a big role in explaining rising costs in sectors such as healthcare, where doctors demand high wages leading to high costs.

College Tuition Costs¶

The price of college tuition has exploded in recent decades, rising on average 6.52% a year and 163% since 1988. This has led to crushing student debt on the shoulders of young people, and represents a major barrier to opportunity for those with lower incomes. Lowering the costs of college would be a large step in increasing social mobility and building a more equitable economy. However, we must first know the cause of the problem to find a solution.

Are Students In For a Baumoling?¶

It's no surprise that Baumol's Cost Disease has been brought up as a major factor in the high cost of higher education. The reasoning goes that professors and faculty are highly qualified individuals that companies and other organizations can poach for high prices. Thus, these professors must be convinced to stay with high wages. Since a college must hire many professors, the productivity of colleges cannot rise, and the colleges are forced to pass the cost of hiring numerous highly-paid faculty on to the students.

This is not, however, taken as fact. There is still a robust debate over how much of an effect the Cost Disease has on rising tuition costs, and there are other causes that have been proposed to be larger factors, such as the revenue theory of costs. This tutorial will attempt to analyze the conditions of higher education and how the cost disease effects them, and how much the cost disease can explain the trend of rising tuition.

The Analysis¶

This tutorial will analyze whether higher education is truly impacted by Baumol's Cost Disease, and how much Baumol's Cost Disease can explain the rise in college tuition prices.

Part 1: Analyzing Conditions for Baumol's Cost Disease¶

To determine is higher education is effected heavily by Baumol's Cost Disease, we must determine two things: that the productivity of higher education is increasing more slowly than other sectors of the economy, and that wages in higher education are rising more quickly than productivity in the sector.

Part 2: Analyzing Effects of Baumol's Cost Disease¶

To determine how much of an effect Baumol's Cost Disease has on college tuition, the spending on salaries of faculty members in higher education will be regressed against revenue sources and other sources of cost to see which cause has the most explanatory power.

Part 1¶

Data Collection and Cleaning¶

We will first gather data describing the salaries of college faculty, productivity, and economy-wide wages.

We can now visualize this data to see if the wages of college faculty are increasing at a rate similar to or less than wages in other sectors. If they're increasing at a rate similar to other sectors, this could be a problem if the productivity of colleges aren't increasing.

We see that the average wage of college faculty is actually increasing at a rate FASTER than the average worker. This means the productivity of higher education would have to increase faster than the productivity of the whole economy to avoid Baumol's Cost Disease.

Next, we need to calculate the productivity of higher education. I could not find any data on the productivity of this sector, as you can't really quantify the value of its output (students with degrees) with a price. So, I'm roughly estimating the productivity. Since our current measurement of productivity is output/employees, I decided a good measure of output would be taught students, and the employees would be faculty. So, productivity in this case would be the student/faculty ratio. Since there was not a nationwide student/faculty ratio recorded, I estimated that by getting the number of students courtesy of Statista, and the number of faculty, I could find it. However, I could not find the number of faculty either. I did find a very detailed dataset about college expenditures maintained by the Delta Cost Project so I decided to use that instead. So the measurement of productivity is (# students educated) / ($ spent on faculty).

To start, I imported the total number of college students in the US. I created the 'total' column to keep track of the public and private students put together

By inspection, we notice that each row is not the total spending for that year, but the spending at one specific college for that year. To get the total spending, we add together the spending at each college for that year. To keep each year in the same magnitude of spending, instead of dropping nans we replace them with the mean amount spent. We then combine this dataframe with the enrollment data to form the total spending and enrollment dataframe, containing all we need to measure productivity.

In [239]:
year_totals = {}
na_counts = {}
for year in range(1987, 2016):
    year_salaries = combined.loc[combined['academicyear'] == year]['instruction02']
    na_counts[year] = year_salaries.isnull().sum()
    year_salaries.fillna(value=year_salaries.mean(), inplace=True)
    year_totals[year] = year_salaries.sum()
In [240]:
year_totals_df = pd.DataFrame(pd.Series(year_totals))
totals_and_enrollment = yearly_enrolled.join(year_totals_df, on="year", how="inner")

Though it certainly appears that productivity is growing faster than educational productivity, the axes for each line are quite different. To see the growth rate, we analyze the percent change per year.

In [254]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
#ax2 = ax.twinx()
ax.plot(productivity_wages['year'], productivity_wages['productivity'].pct_change(), label='Productivity')
ax.plot(totals_and_enrollment['year'], totals_and_enrollment['ed_prod'].pct_change(), color='red', label='Educational Productivity')
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Percent Change of Productivity Since Last Year")
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.show()

We see that educational productivity has been going up at approximately the same rate as regular productivity! This means that faculty spending per college student has been decreasing year onto year, at least very mildly. This could mean faculty members are taking on larger classes, or some other innovation is keeping costs per student down. However, this does not mean that faculty costs as a whole have been going down.
